 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ulorddaeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>lorddaeth</A> at: 7/9/02 11:49:12 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ulorddaeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>lorddaeth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/9/02 11:44:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=119>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  work in progress, same topic, revised my old post.</span><hr size=1> i'm working on composing a letter to verant, i'd like input as i work on this document. i would like some logical input into the discussion, not flames<br>
<br>
letter follows:<br>
I know this is long. but i've seen where general complaints with no background/arguments to show the position get ignored. so for each of the points below i tried to show how i got to that point.  I thank you now for reading this.<br>
<br>
there is a thread right now on steel warriors that i initially just dismissed outright. but after reading some of the points offered up, i started to realize that what they are saying has alot of merit.<br>
<br>
the thread is basically that by using Warriors as the &quot;yardstick&quot; for melee, by raising other classes, and leaving warriors mostly alone, the developers have &quot;reverse nerfed&quot; warriors.<br>
<br>
let's talk a bit first about &quot;the concepts&quot; of the classes. Warriors are the masters of armed combat in all its many forms. They are right at home on the battlefield and are trained to take as much punishment as they dole out, because of their innately strong constitutions. <br>
<br>
A paladin is the very embodiment of a holy knight, fighting for the cause of good in every aspect of his or her life. As the paladin gains life experience and proves his devotion, he will be granted the ability to use limited clerical magics. They share some of the powers of clerics along with a good deal of the fighting ability of warriors, but have a few virtues all their own. <br>
<br>
Shadowknights are exactly what their name implies - beings with the power of knights who live and work in the shadows. The antithesis of the paladin, shadowknights derive all of their powers from the evil gods they serve. Their abilities are a blend of warrior-like skills and necromantic studies.  (taken from <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eqlive.station.sony.com/library/classes.jsp).">eqlive.station.sony.com/l...sses.jsp).</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <br>
<br>
to condense those very verbose paragraphs, Palladins and Shadowknights have forsaken some martial ability to develop the use of spells, where warriors are only interested in martial ability. This basic concept was refelcted by different factors in the game, Armor available, melee tables, and skills. before all this AA mumbo jumbo, and this supposed &quot;class balancing&quot;. warriors fit this description. we stand there and get hit, and deliver hits, we hit taunt to give us that extra bit of aggro to keep the mob standing in front of us. we did not deliver as much damage as a monk or as a rogue because, while they are pure melee classes as well, they are tweaked/pointed into more of an offensive melee rather then the warriors defensive one. Pallies/SK's were classes that traded some of that offensive power and tanking ability to develop the arcane/diving magics. This gave them some utility and versatility. They were no where near the equal of a Warrior in straight combat, they would have to use those spells to compensate for this.<br>
<br>
Paladins and Shadow Knights have been improved in thier ability to take hits and hold aggro while doing so. this is the sole thing that a warrior offers to a group. pally's and SK's can now be just as effective in this role, but also bring thier spells and versatility to the group. Since the game has been launched many changes have come about that have led to the diminishing effectiveness and desireability of a warrior in grind groups and in lesser raids. Let me explain why, starting with defense. <br>
<br>
Warriors are defined from each other (kunark era) ONLY by thier gear. in the days of kunark and earlier this was reflected in the game by the Warr only gear having that extra 10-15% AC compared to the pally/sk items. here are the kunark BPs for example (12.5% better AC with kunark armors)<br>
<br>
War=Cobalt Breastplate +45 AC +12 Str +12 Sta +12 Dex +50 HP +20.00 Wt <br>
SK=Blood Ember Breastplate +40 AC +12 Str +8 Sta +8 Agi +8 Dex +10.00 Wt <br>
Pal=Deepwater Breastplate +40 AC +10 Str +10 Agi +10 Wis +50 Mana +10.00 Wt <br>
<br>
don't forget that this was when you were lucky to have a 1200 AC, much less talking about AC softcaps.<br>
<br>
Today, assuming that you do have all your AA filled in, you once again find that the only thing that defines a tank is his gear. (no, i doubt such a mythic warrior exists at this time, but if wer'e talking balance let's take it to the extreme as that's where the differences will be best seen). the same 10 BP's show up under each under a search on allakhazam's site. (using ACx10, hpx1) for pally, sk and warrior. so this means that pallies, SK's and Warriors can now all have the same AC. <br>
<br>
Great Shadow Platemail <br>
Heavy Yttrium Chestplate<br>
Breastplate of the Void <br>
Breastplate of Speed <br>
Breastplate of Eradication <br>
Chestplate of Fiery Might <br>
True Mithril Breastplate <br>
Breastplate of Superiority <br>
Jenniy's Two-tone Cuirass <br>
Warmaster's Ribcage <br>
<br>
and with the exception of the velious class quested armors, much of the next 10 are the same as well.<br>
<br>
so basically, in the armor category, pallies and SK's are now the same as warriors. this removes the advantage that warriors had in the AC and related HP areas over SK's and pallies.<br>
<br>
then came luclin, with it's AA points. all melee classes got Natural Durability, Combat Stability, Combat Agility. everyone was fine with that. Hybrids also get another AA advancement called Physical Enhancement. This skill add's an additional 2% to each of those 3 prior skills.  This is where the problem starts. now, it was explained that if warriors are considered to be at 100% of &quot;yardstick&quot; and pallies/sk's are considered to be at 75%, then a 10% boost to both yields 110% and 82.5%. this still leaves that 25% lead that warriors are supposed to get, but then with physical enhancement they get an additional 2%. this makes them at 84%. this makes them now 76.3% (84/110=76.3%)as effective again tanks this is a relative 1.3% gain.  according to the smart people out there that like to fiddle with it, a warrior with 255 stam has 3335 base hp before items. a pally has 2891 with 255 stam.  this means that pally/sk have 86% as many hp, before item adds. now with the 10% bonus that warr's get, that's 3668 hp from ND 3, and pally/sk get 3237 with thier 12%, now they are at 88% of a warrior. <br>
<br>
now, the real kicker is, since pallies and SK's wear the same armor that means they get the same HP bonuses that were reserved for warriors. now, say that both the warrior and the pally have +500hp in items, and it's been shown that the AA skills also affect these bonus's so now we have 4218 (1.10*(3335+500)), and 3797 (1.12*(2891+500)), now the pally is at 90% as many hp, because a straigh addition is a larger percent addition if the base it is being added to is smaller (100 added to 100 is a 50% increse, 100 added to 200 is a 33% increase, law of diminishing returns). While HP buffs (aegolism, talismans, etc) do not get the multiplier by adding straigh HP to a character. The relative benefit's are greater on the one with the smaller starting pool.<br>
<br>
the explanation for this extra 2% gain was posted on <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000583.html.">boards.station.sony.com/u...0583.html.</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> The major flaw in this posting is that while a warrior goes from 100 to 110, and a hybrid goes from 75 to 82.5 the hybrid is still 75% of a warrior, even though the warrior gains 10 points, and the hybrid gains 7.5. they are still proportionally the same. but now, with that extra 2 percent they are now 77% of a warrior. they get an extra boost. this extra boost is enlarged with +hp items. and if you go by straight HP, they are not 75%, they are 86% by base hp. and that gap is shortened with any +hp item. and while HP buffs (aegolism, talismans, etc) do not get the multiplier by adding straigh HP to a character, but the relative benefit's are greater on the one with the smaller starting pool.<br>
<br>
So, when you have a Warrior and a Pally/SK standing next to each other. with the same gear on, with ND3, CA3, CS3, and PE for the hybrid, Aegolism (1100 hp), Focus of Spirit (405 hp)and +1000 hp from items, you get the warrior having 6273 hp, and the pally/SK having 5862 hp, now the pally/sk is at 93% of HP, where they were at 86% standing nekked.<br>
<br>
also, it has been shown and confirmed that there is an AC softcap around 1250. combat stability/agility push this softcap to 1375 for warriors, and 1400 for hybrids. so now, while we have 6% more hp, they have 2% better AC then us, you know, the guys that eschewed all other skills other then the ability to fight.<br>
<br>
now onto offense. no matter what weapon your wielding, its what offensive category/bracket your in that defines just how much you can do offensivly. and from the oct 8 2001 patch, we get the biggest of the &quot;balancing changes&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;Paladins and Shadowknights, besides the benefits they gain from the two-handed weapons change mentioned above, have also been moved to the same combat tables as warriors. In the future we intend to examine the existing one-handed weapons useable by knights for possible upgrades. We are also increasing the Taunt skill cap for these two classes to 220.&quot;<br>
<br>
basically, we went from &quot;Masters of combat&quot; to being the same as the pallies and SK's. you know, those guys who gave up some offensive power to cast spells.<br>
<br>
now let's talk about other upgrades the pallies and SK's got. from <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000135.html">boards.station.sony.com/u...00135.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> we get &quot;Recently we removed the mana pool difference and significantly reduced the casting cost difference. We also gave the hybrid the advantage of unique spells and a significantly reduced penalty for casting while fighting (weapon delays continue to count off while spells are being cast – only for hybirds). In combination, all of those changes make for a very nice balance of spell casting power and melee power for the hybrids.&quot;<br>
<br>
okie, so now, they get to cast more spells, and their weapon delay is not reset when they cast a spell. cool for them. but now that they have this increase, their damage abilities have gotten a significant boost. <br>
<br>
so now thier DPS is even to, or greater than that of warriors. (in the thread this letter comes from, some people have posted actual combat parsed data showing this from a reliable high end guild {page23 of the post} <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showMessageRange?topicID=907.topic&start=441&stop=460).">pub14.ezboard.com/ftheste...stop=460).</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
so, when we gave up the ability to cast spells, or backstab, or deal out damage with special kicks to be the &quot;masters of combat&quot; in the earliest of &quot;game concepts&quot;, pallies/sk's sacraficed this martial ability by learning spells, and it made sense. now they get everything a tank does, AND get thier spells too.<br>
<br>
to counter this, you say in the melee balance post &quot;The &quot;Defensive&quot; discipline is also somewhat overpowered, but many high-end encounters now factor in this discipline in their design so this also remains unchanged.&quot;<br>
<br>
so now our defensive discipline has been &quot;factored in&quot; to encounters and as many high end warriors say that defensive is a crutch. we trade our offensive ability in DPS to take half the DI of the mobs damage (currently the used terms on the boards are mob damage is DI*(randon number between 1 and 20)+DB, where DI is damage increment, and DB is Damage bonus). but to keep aggro, what many are doing is upping the speed of cleric rotations so that the tank can maintain the taunt generated by his damage output. <br>
<br>
so, using this tactic, warriors are no different then paladins and SK now in melee ability. throw in the added aggro that can be generated by the spells they cast and paladins and Shadowknights become the optimal choice for playing the Main Tank role. as this realization sinks in, a few guilds are using these two classes as main tanks for high end encounters.<br>
<br>
now to summarize. through the new armor, new weapons, class balancing, and caster balancing the Role of the warrior according to &quot;the vision&quot; has been effectivly elimiated by blurring the class distinctions.<br>
<br>
now, because i don't want to just seem like complaining. here are a few of the more credible suggestions introduced on the same thread. all of these are for warrior only, as giving them to anyone else would make the alteration useless in the way of balancing the warrior class back against the rest of the field<br>
<br>
1) the most popular suggestion is to have warriors on thier own melee table. where monks are on a table that increases thier offense. put the warriors on one that increases ther defensive abilities. even a 10% reduction of the DI of mobs would see a noticeable effect on our ability to take hits during combat, and not be too overpowering, and it would affect warriors of all levels. <br>
2) allow warriors taunt to affect mobs of any level when they are level 60. allow taunt to have a direct addition to the hate list equal to thier skill, not a chance of working. similar to Eraging Blow weapons.<br>
3) raise the base AC softcap by 100-200 points. this would be similar to number 1, but would mainly affect warriors that are in end game style armors.<br>
<br>
warriors are quickly loosing their Role and desireablility at all levels of play. we have been replaces by sk's and pallies in all but 1% of end mobs. this is what we are asking verant to take a look at if they ever read this letter<br>
<br>
or did i miss something? and thanks for reading it all.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
have a nice day. <p><img src="http://www.xmission.com/~pitchers/klaumbaz.gif"><br>
